\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Project Designation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
An initiative qualifies for formal project designation when it (a) requires three (3) or more discrete work orders to complete,
 and (b) requires advance resource planning,
 stakeholder coordination,
 or sequenced task dependencies that cannot be captured within a single work order record.
 Both conditions shall be satisfied for threshold-based designation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director or IT Director may designate any initiative as a formal project regardless of whether it meets the threshold criteria.
 No initiative may self-designate as a project below the threshold without authorization from the Assistant IT Director or IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Emergency Designation
\series default
:
 An initiative may be formally designated as a project after work has already begun when urgency precludes advance charter preparation —
 for example,
 a county-mandated security remediation requiring an immediate multi-work-order response.
 Emergency designation requires IT Director authorization.
 Catch-up documentation,
 including the project charter,
 risk log,
 stakeholder map,
 and all other required project record elements defined in Section 6.10,
 shall be completed and attached to the master work order within five (5) business days of emergency designation.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Constraint
\series default
:
 Emergency designation waives the advance charter approval requirement only.
 It does not waive the documentation requirements enumerated in Section 6.10,
 the change classification obligations under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Change Management Policy),
 or the CMDB and Knowledge Base closure gates.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall review emergency project designations in aggregate no less than annually as part of the maturity scoring process defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Project Record Structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Each formally designated project shall be represented in the System of Engagement as a master work order,
 which serves as the project record and coordination hub.
 The master work order shall have the Internal Project checkbox set per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and work order operational standards maintained in the System of Engagement.
 Individual task units shall be created as child work orders and linked to the master via the Related Issues field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 Post-Implementation Review (PIR) fires on any Significant or Emergency change within a child work order per the timelines and mechanics established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 This is a change-level obligation that runs independently of this policy.
 A separate project post-mortem under Section 6.7 fires when the master work order closes,
 covering the initiative as a whole.
 These two (2) obligations are parallel and distinct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Phase 1 —
 Initiation and Charter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall designate a Project Owner at charter for every formally designated project.
 Project Owner is a functional designation assigned per-project to an existing role holder —
 IT Director,
 Assistant IT Director,
 Information Operations Systems Administrator,
 or Information Operations Network Administrator.
